---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Words Ending in OUS — The Adjective Powerhouse Suffix for Scrabble"
  description="Top Scrabble words ending in OUS with point values, bingo potential, and strategic placement tips. Free guide with scoring tips and board placement. Free."
  keywords="scrabble words ending in ous, ous words scrabble, words with ous suffix, scrabble bingo ous, high scoring ous words, scrabble suffix ous strategy"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Words Ending in OUS — The Adjective Powerhouse Suffix for Scrabble",
    "description": "Top Scrabble words ending in OUS with point values, bingo potential, and strategic placement tips. Master the 3-letter suffix that creates high-scoring adjectives.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-14",
    "author": { "@type": "Person", "name": "Raj Naik", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/about/" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/words-ending-in-ous" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the highest scoring Scrabble words ending in OUS?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "HAZARDOUS (22 pts), LUXURIOUS (19 pts), and OBNOXIOUS (18 pts) are among the highest-scoring -OUS words. These combine high-value root letters (Z, X, J) with the OUS suffix for impressive base scores that multiply on premium squares." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is OUS good for Scrabble bingo plays?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — OUS is excellent for bingos because it only uses 3 tiles (O=1, U=1, S=1), leaving 4 tiles for the root word. This gives you more room for complex roots while still reaching the 7-letter bingo threshold. Words like FAMOUS, POROUS, and JOYOUS demonstrate how short roots + OUS = efficient bingos." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What makes OUS different from other adjective suffixes like ABLE?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "OUS uses only 3 tiles versus ABLE's 4, giving you more root flexibility. However, OUS has a lower base point value (3 pts vs ABLE's 6). The key advantage is that OUS words are often shorter (6-8 letters), making them easier to fit on congested boards while still qualifying for bingos at 7+ letters." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 pt-4 pb-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">Word Lists</span>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Words Ending in OUS — The Adjective Powerhouse Suffix for Scrabble</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-14">June 14, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔍</span> Solver</a> <a href="/activities/#quiz" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎯</span> Quiz</a> <a href="/activities/#anagram" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔀</span> Anagram</a> <a href="/activities/#rack" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎲</span> Rack</a> <a href="/activities/#wotd" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">📖</span> WOTD</a> <a href="/sixty-seconds/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">⏱️</span> 60s</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        The -OUS suffix creates adjectives from nouns and Latin roots — and in Scrabble, it creates scoring opportunities from compact letter combinations. Unlike the 4-letter heavyweights (TION, NESS, MENT, ABLE), OUS uses just 3 tiles, leaving you 4 full tiles for the root word. This extra root flexibility means you can build longer, more complex bingo words while the lightweight suffix tags along for the ride. Master OUS words and you'll find bingos hiding in racks others dismiss as unplayable.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">High-Scoring Words Ending in OUS</h2>

      <p>These -OUS words deliver top scores by combining premium root consonants with the light suffix. The extra root tile allowance means more room for high-value letters like Z, X, and J.</p>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">#</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Points</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Length</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Definition</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">1</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">HAZARDOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">22</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">9</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Involving danger or risk</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">2</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">LUXURIOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">19</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">9</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Extremely comfortable</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">3</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">VEXATIOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">19</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">9</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Causing annoyance</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">4</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">OBNOXIOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">18</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">9</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Extremely unpleasant</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">5</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">JOYOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">16</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">6</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Full of joy</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">6</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">JEALOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">14</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">7</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Envious of another</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">7</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">VIGOROUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">13</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">8</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Strong and active</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">8</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">WONDROUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">8</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Inspiring wonder</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">9</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">GRIEVOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">8</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Very severe or serious</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">10</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">FIBROUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">7</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Containing fibres</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">11</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">FAMOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">11</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">6</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Known by many</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">12</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">GLORIOUS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400">10</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">8</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Magnificent or splendid</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3 tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Suffix commitment</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">700+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid -OUS words</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">4 root</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Tiles available for root</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The 3-Tile Advantage</h2>

      <p>OUS is unique among longer suffixes because it only uses 3 rack tiles. This seemingly small difference gives you a fundamentally different bingo dynamic compared to 4-tile suffixes.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The OUS Root Flexibility</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">With only 3 suffix tiles (O, U, S), you have <span class="text-white font-medium">4 full tiles for the root word</span>. This means you can build with roots like FAMO (FAMOUS), JEALO (JEALOUS), VIGOR (VIGOROUS), or GLORI (GLORIOUS). Four root tiles give you more complex combinations — and more letters to place on premium squares.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Short OUS Words for Quick Plays</h2>

      <p>Several OUS words are only 6 letters — short enough for any board position, yet common enough to play frequently. These are your bread-and-butter OUS plays.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">JOYOUS</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">16 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">FAMOUS</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">11 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">POROUS</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">8 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">MUCOUS</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">10 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">FIBROUS</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">NERVOUS</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">10 pts</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Bingo Strategy with OUS</h2>

      <p>The 3-tile suffix means you need 4 root tiles for a 7-letter bingo. This gives you more complex root words — and more high-value letters in play.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">4-tile root bingos:</span> JEALOUS (JEAL+OUS), ZEALOUS (ZEAL+OUS), NERVOUS (NERV+OUS), FIBROUS (FIBR+OUS). With 4 root tiles, you have room for high-value letters like J, Z, X in the root portion.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">8-9 letter extensions:</span> GLORIOUS, VIGOROUS, GENEROUS, WONDROUS — these extend your reach across the board. Five root tiles + OUS = 8 letters hitting multiple premium square zones.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">The S tile bonus:</span> OUS ends with S — the most valuable hooking letter in Scrabble. Playing an OUS word means you've used your S productively as part of a suffix rather than as a simple hook for 1-2 extra points.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">U tile utilisation:</span> U is often a problematic tile — low value (1 pt) and hard to place. OUS gives you a productive use for U, converting a liability tile into part of a scoring suffix.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Premium Square Positioning</h2>

      <p>OUS words benefit from having more root letters available for premium squares. With 4-5 root tiles potentially carrying high values, your scoring multiplier opportunities increase.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Z on Triple Letter</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">HAZARDOUS with Z on TLS = 30 from one tile. The extra root letters in OUS words mean more chances to land premium letters on multipliers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ 9-Letter Board Span</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">HAZARDOUS (9 letters, 22 pts) crossing TWS = 66 + 50 bingo bonus = 116 points. OUS words frequently reach 8-9 letters for maximum board coverage.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Hold OUS</h2>

      <p>OUS has the lightest suffix commitment of the group — just 3 tiles. This makes it the safest hold because you sacrifice less scoring power while waiting for the bingo.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3 tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Lightest suffix hold</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">4 root</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Maximum root flexibility</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">2-3 turns</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Acceptable hold time</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Because OUS only commits 3 tiles, you can afford to hold it slightly longer than 4-tile suffixes. If your remaining 4 tiles include common root patterns (FAMO, GLORI, VIGOR, NERV), play immediately. Otherwise, you can hold for 2-3 turns without catastrophic opportunity cost — the suffix tiles (O, U, S) are low-value individually anyway.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Summary</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎯 Summary</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The -OUS suffix is your <span class="text-white font-medium">lightest bingo suffix with maximum root flexibility</span>. Using only 3 tiles, it leaves 4 for the root — meaning more room for high-value letters and complex combinations. Over 700 valid OUS words exist, the suffix productively uses the often-problematic U tile, and OUS words consistently reach 8-9 letters for premium square coverage. It's the safest suffix hold in Scrabble: low commitment, high bingo potential, and flexible enough to work with almost any rack combination.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/words-ending-in-ly/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Words Ending in LY — The Adverb Suffix Strategy</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/hooking-existing-words/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Hooking Existing Words — Extend for Maximum Points</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/six-letter-words-that-lead-to-bingos/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Six-Letter Words That Lead to Bingos</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-900/20 to-blue-800/20 border border-blue-800 rounded-xl">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-blue-300 font-medium">🔍 Find -OUS words from your rack tiles — instant results, no signup</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-blue-500 hover:bg-blue-400 text-gray-950 text-sm font-semibold transition-colors">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
